            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Chloe Amari\u2019s life began not in the city\u2019s electric hum, but in the quiet, tree-lined streets of Alameda. Raised by two intellectually sharp but emotionally reserved parents\u2014a physicist and a logician\u2014Chloe learned early that feelings were messy variables best left out of the equation. Words were for debate, not comfort. For Chloe, expression found its home in charcoal sketches and watercolor bleeds, a silent language her family didn't quite understand but tolerated. This disconnect fueled her fascination with the psyche, leading her to UC Santa Cruz for a degree in Psychology.\n\nHer university years were a time of profound self-discovery. She fell in love, married young, and divorced just as quickly, keeping the surname Amari as a quiet rebellion and a testament to an identity she was forging for herself. It was during this tumultuous period she realized traditional talk therapy felt incomplete. She discovered the field of art therapy, a perfect synthesis of her childhood coping mechanism and her academic passion. After earning her certifications, she moved to San Francisco, drawn to its embrace of the unconventional.\n\nNow 41, Chloe has built a life of quiet purpose. She lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond, a peaceful enclave from which she commutes 3.5 miles on the 5-Fulton MUNI bus to a community health center where she works with at-risk youth. Her days are a collage of listening, creating, and helping kids find their own visual language for trauma and hope. Her $82,000 salary affords a modest but comfortable life, prioritized on experiences over possessions.\n\nHer evenings often involve long walks through Golden Gate Park with Otis, her scruffy terrier mix, followed by cooking or reading. Her social circle is a tight-knit group of friends met through work and a pottery class, with whom she shares dinners and weekend trips to the coast. While content, Chloe dreams of one day opening a small, independent art therapy studio in the Mission, a space accessible to all, funded by community support. For her, San Francisco is not just a home; it's a canvas, and she is still finding new colors to add to her life's work."
